^B@2^*Blrargerich: ^*N|cp||at|1 level contracts require only 7 tricks. So unless you can call an ambulance before passing 1x doubled don't do it. My advice is that you should have 6 trumps to pass 1x doubled and 5 trumps to pass 2x doubled. Many bad things can happen. They may win 1x doubled when your side has a part score. They can go down 1 when you had a game available, etc. So I pass with 6 trumps at the 1 level or with 5 at the 2 level. I usually want to have GOOD texture in the suit. For example A5432 is not good at all to pass a takeout double. JT987 is better than A5432 because the ace will take a trick in defense and will also take a trick if you play the hand. While the JT987 won't take a trick if you play in a suit but can take 2 in defense.|
PG| ***** 7 ***** |


cp|8|AT|

^B@2^*Blrargerich: ^*N|cp||at|1NT is always constructive so please never bid 1NT with nothing. When we have a very bad hand and partner has doubled 1m we pick the best major we have and bid 1M. We should even prefer 1H with 3 cards to say 1NT or 2@C when we have nothing. That's why we need some way do distinguish 0 HCP from say 9 HCP. Otherwise partner won't know what to do. The most standard approach is:|
PG| ***** 8 ***** |


ht|q|fp|2|at|Bidding 1M with less than 8 hcp and 3+ cards;|
PG| ***** 9 ***** |


ht|q|at|Bidding 1M with less than 8 hcp and 3+ cards;|
ht|s|at|Jump to 2M when you have about 8-11 HCP and 4 cards in a major;|
PG| ***** 10 ***** |


ht|q|at|Bidding 1M with less than 8 hcp and 3+ cards;|
ht|s|at|Jump to 2M when you have about 8-11 HCP and 4 cards in a major;|
ht|u|at|Jumping to 3M with the same strength and 5 cards.;|
PG| ***** 11 ***** |


ht|q|at|Bidding 1M with less than 8 hcp and 3+ cards;|
ht|s|at|Jump to 2M when you have about 8-11 HCP and 4 cards in a major;|
ht|u|at|Jumping to 3M with the same strength and 5 cards.;|AND
ht|w|at|1NT would be 7-10HCP and a balanced hand without 4 cards in a major.|
