^B@2^*BHoward Schutzman: ^*N|cp||at|The most important thing to remember is that you cannot pass over a takeout double, even if you have a bad hand—MM may have to call 911 -:). Partner is demanding that you bid, and understands that you may not have a very good hand. The most common method of responding to takeout doubles is (assuming your right hand opponent has passed):|
PG| ***** 14 ***** |


HT|h|at|^B@21) With less than 9 points, bid a 4 card major if you have one; otherwise bid your best minor.|
PG| ***** 15 ***** |


HT|h|at|^B@21) With less than 9 points, bid a 4 card major if you have one; otherwise bid your best minor.|
HT|i|at|^B@22) With an intermediate hand, jump one level, preferring a 4 card major over a minor suit. For example, bid 2@S or 3@C if partner has doubled a 1@H opener.|
PG| ***** 16 ***** |


HT|h|at|^B@21) With less than 9 points, bid a 4 card major if you have one; otherwise bid your best minor.|
HT|i|at|^B@22) With an intermediate hand, jump one level, preferring a 4 card major over a minor suit. For example, bid 2@S or 3@C if partner has doubled a 1@H opener.|
HT|k|at|^B@23) With an opening hand, you have game. Let partner know this by cue bidding the opponent's opening suit. For example, bid 2@H if partner has doubled a 1@H bid.|
PG| ***** 17 ***** |


HT|h|at|^B@21) With less than 9 points, bid a 4 card major if you have one; otherwise bid your best minor.|
HT|i|at|^B@22) With an intermediate hand, jump one level, preferring a 4 card major over a minor suit. For example, bid 2@S or 3@C if partner has doubled a 1@H opener.|
HT|k|at|^B@23) With an opening hand, you have game. Let partner know this by cue bidding the opponent's opening suit. For example, bid 2@H if partner has doubled a 1@H bid.|
HT|m|at|^B@2Remember, as takeout doubler, partner already knows you have an opening hand. Therefore, you should pass any non-cue bid unless you have better than a minimum opener.|
