{  A Summary by Barbara Seagram  }
^-|fp||
pg| ***** 74 ***** |


at|^-
{  You must respond to a takeout double, no matter how weak your hand, except on the rare occasion that you  
actually want to defend their doubled contract.}
|
PG| ***** 75 ***** |


AT|
{  Making the minimum response in your longest suit does not show any values — i.e. you could hold zero points.  }
|
PG| ***** 76 ***** |


AT|
{  With 9-11 points (including distribution), jump in your longest suit.  }
|
PG| ***** 77 ***** |


AT|
{  With 12+ points, you can force to game by cuebiding opener’s  suit or you can just jump to game if  
you have a five—card major.}
|
PG| ***** 78 ***** |


AT|
{  Notrump responses to a takeout double show positive values.  }
|
PG| ***** 79 ***** |


AT|
{1NT shows 8-10 HCP 2NT 11-12, and 3NT 13+. 
    You must also have at least one stopper (and preferably two) in the opener’s suit    
remember that partner will be short in that suit.} 
|
PG| ***** 80 ***** |


AT|
{    If RHO intervenes over partner’s double, you can pass with a bad hand.    }
|
PG| ***** 81 ***** |


AT|
{  Making a free bid therefore shows some values (8+ points including distribution  }.
|
PG| ***** 82 ***** |


AT|
{    If you double a new suit bid by RHO, you are showing length in that suit and some values.      
If RHO raises opener’s suit, you can use a responsive double to describe certain types of hands.} 
|
PG| ***** 83 ***** |


AT|
{  Bids after RHO has redoubled do not show values, just a long suit. Jumps are preemptive, rather than showing values.  }
^-|
PG| ***** 84 ***** |


